{{Quote|A strained voice, a realization that anyone could have done it, and great pleasure at having been chosen.|Ed Asner, commenting on what he gained as a result of voicing Jabba for the ''Return of the Jedi'' radio production|<ref name="Radio Days">{{InsiderCite|73|Radio Days: Revisiting the Star Wars Radio Dramas}}</ref>}}
'''Ed Asner''', born '''Eddie Asner''' and also credited as '''Edward Asner''' ([[November 15]], [[1920s#1929|1929]] - [[August 29]], [[2021]]), was an [[Wikipedia:Americans|American]] actor and voice actor known to television audiences for his role as [[Wikipedia:Lou Grant (fictional character)|Lou Grant]] on [[Wikipedia:The Mary Tyler Moore Show|''The Mary Tyler Moore Show'']] and its spinoff, [[Wikipedia:Lou Grant (TV series)|''Lou Grant'']]. He voiced [[Jabba Desilijic Tiure/Legends|Jabba the Hutt]] in the [[1996]] [[Return of the Jedi (radio)|radio adaptation]] of the film [[Star Wars: Episode VI Return of the Jedi|''Star Wars'': Episode VI ''Return of the Jedi'']], recreating the character's [[Huttese/Legends|Huttese]] dialogue without any electronic effects at his insistence. Asner later became the voice of [[Jedi Master]] [[Vrook Lamar]] in the [[2003]] [[Star Wars video games|video game]] ''[[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic]]''. The character's original voice actor, [[Pat Fraley]], insisted on calling Asner for the part after seeing his name listed as a reference point for the character's voice. Asner later reprised the role in the game's [[2004]] sequel, [[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic II: The Sith Lords|''The Sith Lords'']].

==Biography==
===Early life and ''Return of the Jedi''===
{{Quote|I wanted to emulate the movie Jabba as much as possible, so I gained 5,000 pounds. Didn't do much for my love life though.|Ed Asner|<ref name="Radio Days" />}}
Ed Asner was an [[Wikipedia:American|American]] actor and voice actor,<ref name="Death" /> born Eddie Asner<ref name="Birthname">{{Twitter|TheOnlyEdAsner|status/1167899086923517955|Ed Asner|date=31-08-2019|quote="My real name is Eddie Asner. Truth."|archivedate=20190912082147}}</ref> on [[November 15]], [[1920s#1929|1929]] in [[Wikipedia:Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City, Missouri]], [[Wikipedia:United States|United States]].<ref name="Death" /> He worked as a voice actor in radio productions as a teenager<ref name="Radio Days" /> and rose to prominence in the 1970s-80s as [[Wikipedia:Lou Grant (fictional character)|Lou Grant]] on [[Wikipedia:The Mary Tyler Moore Show|''The Mary Tyler Moore Show'']] and its spinoff, [[Wikipedia:Lou Grant (TV series)|''Lou Grant'']], receiving numerous accolades.<ref name="Death" />

[[File:JabbaHookah-ROTJ.png|thumb|right|300px|Ed Asner's first ''Star Wars'' role was as the voice of Jabba the Hutt (pictured) in the radio adaptation of ''Return of the Jedi''.]]
In [[1996]], he was cast as the [[Crime lord/Legends|crime lord]] [[Jabba Desilijic Tiure/Legends|Jabba the Hutt]] in the [[National Public Radio]] (NPR) [[Return of the Jedi (radio)|adaptation]]<ref name="Radio">[[Return of the Jedi (radio)|''Return of the Jedi'' radio drama]]</ref> of the [[1983]] [[original trilogy]] film, [[Star Wars: Episode VI Return of the Jedi|''Star Wars'': Episode VI ''Return of the Jedi'']].<ref name="ROTJ">{{Film|VI}}</ref> Asner's notoriety meant that his casting drew attention to the production. He enjoyed the opportunity to contribute to a radio production like those of his youth,<ref name="Radio Days" /> although he had not seen a ''[[Star Wars]]'' film at that time.<ref name="Starlog">{{Starlog|236|Starlog (magazine)|Being Threepio}}</ref> In an [[Return of the Radio Drama|article]] about the radio production, writer [[Kevin Burke]] commented that his role as Lou Grant may have informed his performance as the corpulent and aggressive [[Hutt/Legends|Hutt]].<ref name="Return of the Radio Drama">{{InsiderCite|30|Return of the Radio Drama}}</ref>

Although he was initially unsure of how he would perform a non&ndash;[[Wikipedia:English language|English language]] role,<ref name="Starlog" /> Asner insisted on portraying Jabba<ref name="Radio Days" />&mdash;whose dialogue is entirely in the fictional [[Huttese/Legends|Huttese]] language<ref name="Radio" />&mdash;without the aid of electronic effects. He was also highly physical while recording his lines, describing himself as blowing up like a bullfrog as he spoke. As such, his costars would cram the studio to watch his performance, regardless of whether their presence was required.<ref name="Radio Days" /> [[Anthony Daniels]], who portrayed the [[3PO-series protocol droid/Legends|protocol droid]] [[C-3PO/Legends|C-3PO]], would crane his neck to watch Asner down the corridor<ref name="Radio script">[[Return of the Jedi: The National Public Radio Dramatization|''Return of the Jedi'': The National Public Radio Dramatization]]</ref> from the privacy of his own booth.<ref name="Starlog" />

During the recording sessions, Asner and several main cast members recorded a humorous goodwill message for [[Brian Daley]], the radio drama's writer, who was ill with pancreatic cancer. Asner's contribution was to speak in Huttese dialogue before telling Daley to get well in slowly spoken English and falling asleep snoring.<ref name="Remembering Brian Daley">{{InsiderCite|55|Remembering Brian Daley}}</ref> Recording took place throughout [[February]] 1996, concluding on the [[February 11|11th]],<ref name="30 years">{{InsiderCite|128|30 Years of Star Wars Radio Drama Part II: How the Empire Almost Won and the Jedi Never Returned}}</ref> and the radio production began broadcasting on [[November 5]] of that year.<ref name="Airdate">{{BookCite|author=Sterling, Christopher|container=''Star Wars''|title=Encyclopedia of Radio|number=vol. 3|publisher=[[Wikipedia:Museum of Broadcast Communications|Museum of Broadcast Communications]]|date=2004|isbn=9781135456498|quote=The finished product was given to NPR, which broadcast it beginning 5 November 1996}}</ref> Asner was credited as "Edward Asner" in the production.<ref name="Radio" />

In a later interview about the [[Star Wars radio dramas|''Star Wars'' radio series]], Asner recalled a highly positive atmosphere in the recording studio, joking that Daley and director [[John Madden]] had been added to his will. He also commented that he would leap at the chance to play the slightly younger Jabba if adaptations of the [[prequel trilogy]] films were ever produced.<ref name="Radio Days" />

===''Knights of the Old Republic''===
{{Quote|He's in there chewing gum, and I'm too scared to say anything. And Pat Fraley's sitting there, and he's like, 'Hey, Ed. Get your gum!' And so Ed Asner takes his gum out, throws it in the trash, and he just starts recording.|Voice-over director Darragh O'Farrell, recalling Asner's recording session for ''Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic''|<ref name="Making of">{{BookCite|author=[[Alex Kane|Kane, Alex]]|title=Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic|publisher=[[Wikipedia:Boss Fight Books|Boss Fight Books]]|date=2019|isbn=1940535212}}</ref>}}
During the end of production of the [[BioWare]] and [[LucasArts]] [[Star Wars video games|video game]] ''[[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic]]'', Asner's voice was used as a reference point in the casting notes for the character of [[Jedi Master/Legends|Jedi Master]] [[Vrook Lamar]]. Voice actor [[Pat Fraley]] was originally cast as the character, but when he arrived to record dialogue, he offered to contact Asner, as they lived across the street from each other. To the surprise and terror of voice-over director [[Darragh O'Farrell]], who was unsure as to whether LucasArts could afford the veteran actor, Fraley immediately telephoned Asner, who promptly arrived at the recording studio.<ref name="Making of" />

[[File:Vrookfull.png|thumb|left|200px|The casting notes for Vrook Lamar (pictured) used Ed Asner's voice as a reference point, which resulted in Asner himself taking the role.]]
O'Farrell's attempts to describe the character as a Jedi were initially puzzling to Asner until he compared the character to "the [[Alec Guinness]] sort of thing," referring to that actor's portrayal of Jedi Master [[Obi-Wan Kenobi]] in the original trilogy of ''Star Wars'' films. O'Farrell was too intimidated to ask Asner to remove the gum he had been chewing when he arrived at the studio until Fraley stepped in. The character's total dialogue took two hours to record. O'Farrell still felt intimidated as he pulled out the paperwork for Asner to sign for his paycheck, but the actor instead continued chatting to the voice-over director and signed the paperwork without even looking at it.<ref name="Making of" />

On [[May 23]], [[2003]], an article on the gaming website [[Wikipedia:IGN|''IGN'']] confirmed Asner's casting as Lamar. The article's author, [[Wikipedia:Aaron Boulding|Aaron Boulding]], believed that his numerous film portrayals as "gruff and sometimes kind-hearted characters" would suit his role as a member of the [[Jedi High Council/Legends|Jedi High Council]].<ref name="IGN">{{WebCite|url=http://xbox.ign.com/articles/410/410156p1.html|text=Voices of the Old Republic|author=[[Wikipedia:Aaron Boulding|Boulding, Aaron]]|date=23-05-2003|work=[[Wikipedia:IGN|''IGN'']]|archivedate=20040417134250}}</ref> ''Knights of the Old Republic'' was first released on the [[Wikipedia:Xbox|Xbox]] console on [[July 15]], [[2003]].<ref name="Anniversary">{{SW|url=news/kotor-galaxy-of-heroes|text=BioWare and Capital Games on Bringing ''KotOR'' Fan Favorites into ''Galaxy of Heroes''|nolive=1}}</ref> Later that year, Asner was interviewed about his role in the ''Return of the Jedi'' radio production in the article "[[Radio Days: Revisiting the Star Wars Radio Dramas|Radio Days: Revisiting the ''Star Wars'' Radio Dramas]]" by [[Rich Handley]], included in the [[Star Wars Insider 73|seventy-third issue]] of the ''[[Star Wars Insider]]'' magazine<ref name="Radio Days" /> mailed to subscribers on [[December 26]], 2003 and released on newsstands on [[January 13]], [[2004]].<ref name="SW.com">{{SWArchive|url=community/news/2003/12/news20031219.html|text=Mark Hamill On Stage In ''Insider'' #73}}</ref> In the interview, he described himself as a ''Star Wars'' fan.<ref name="Radio Days" /> Asner reprised the role of Lamar in the sequel to ''Knights of the Old Republic'', [[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic II: The Sith Lords|''The Sith Lords'']],<ref name="KOTOR II">''[[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic II: The Sith Lords]]''</ref> which was first released on Xbox on [[December 6]], 2004.<ref name="Gamespot">{{GameSpot|url=star-wars-knights-of-the-old-republic-ii-the-sit|text=Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic II &ndash; The Sith Lords}}</ref> Asner died in his home on [[August 29]], [[2021]] in [[Wikipedia:Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], [[Wikipedia:California|California]].<ref name="Death" />

